In [34]:
def check_data_quality(df, name):
    print(f"\n--- {name} ---")
    print("Shape:", df.shape)
    print("Null values:\n", df.isnull().sum())
    print("Duplicate rows:", df.duplicated().sum())

check_data_quality(student_df, "StudentUser")
check_data_quality(meal_df, "MealSlot")
check_data_quality(booking_df, "BookingRecord")
check_data_quality(special_df, "SpecialOrderSlot")

Count bookings per meal type¶

In [109]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
ax = sns.barplot(data=meal_counts, x="meal_type", y="count", color="skyblue")

for p in ax.patches:
    ax.annotate(str(int(p.get_height())),
                (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()),
                ha='center', va='bottom')

plt.title("Bookings per Meal Type")
plt.xlabel("Meal Type")
plt.ylabel("Number of Bookings")
plt.show()

This bar chart clearly shows that Lunch and Dinner are the most popular meals, with very similar booking counts. Breakfast has the lowest demand. This insight is crucial for the mess to allocate resources and staff more effectively during peak hours.¶

Trends over time (daily)¶

In [136]:
if "booked_at" in booking_full.columns:
    booking_full["booked_at"] = pd.to_datetime(booking_full["booked_at"], errors="coerce")

    daily_trend = booking_full.groupby(booking_full["booked_at"].dt.date)["name"].count()

    plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
    plt.plot(daily_trend.index, daily_trend.values, marker="o")
    plt.title("Daily Meal Booking Trend")
    plt.xlabel("Date")
    plt.ylabel("Number of Bookings")
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Daily meal bookings fluctuate between 950 and 1200, with noticeable peaks above 1150 and dips near 950, suggesting that the mess should plan food preparation within this range to handle varying daily demand efficiently.¶

Trends over time (weekly)¶

In [140]:
if "booked_at" in booking_full.columns:
    booking_full["week"] = booking_full["booked_at"].dt.to_period("W").apply(lambda r: r.start_time)
    weekly_trend = booking_full.groupby("week")["name"].count()

    plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
    plt.plot(weekly_trend.index, weekly_trend.values, marker="o", color="green")
    plt.title("Weekly Meal Booking Trend")
    plt.xlabel("Week")
    plt.ylabel("Number of Bookings")
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Weekly meal bookings generally stabilize between 6,200 and 7,500, showing consistent demand across weeks, except for the final week (~3,100) which is incomplete, indicating that weekly planning can be based on an average of ~7,000 bookings.¶

Heatmap: Day of Week vs Meal Type¶

In [186]:
booking_full["day_of_week"] = pd.to_datetime(booking_full["date"]).dt.day_name()
heatmap_data = booking_full.groupby(["day_of_week", "name_meal"]).size().reset_index(name="count")
heatmap_pivot = heatmap_data.pivot(index="day_of_week", columns="name_meal", values="count")

weekday_order = ["Monday","Tuesday","Wednesday","Thursday","Friday","Saturday","Sunday"]
heatmap_pivot = heatmap_pivot.reindex(weekday_order)

plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
sns.heatmap(heatmap_pivot, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="YlGnBu")
plt.title("Meal Bookings Heatmap (Day vs Meal Type)")
plt.xlabel("Meal Type")
plt.ylabel("Day of Week")
plt.show()

he canteen sees its busiest days on Tuesday and Wednesday, when bookings cross 1,800 per meal. This might be because more people are on campus, or simply because the food is tastier and more popular midweek. On weekends, bookings drop to ~1,400, as fewer people order food, possibly choosing to eat out or cook at home.¶

Cancellation % per meal¶

In [343]:
meal_cancel = booking_full.groupby(['name_meal', 'status']).size().reset_index(name='count')
meal_total = booking_full.groupby('name_meal').size().reset_index(name='total')
meal_cancel = pd.merge(meal_cancel, meal_total, on="name_meal")
meal_cancel['cancel_pct'] = (meal_cancel['count'] / meal_cancel['total']) * 100

cancel_data = meal_cancel[meal_cancel['status'].str.lower() == 'canceled']

print(cancel_data)  

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
sns.barplot(data=cancel_data,
            x="name_meal", y="cancel_pct", hue="name_meal", legend=False)
plt.title("Cancellation % per Meal")
plt.ylabel("Cancellation %")
plt.xlabel("Meal Type")
plt.show()

Analysis of Average Available Slots per Day of the Week by Meal Type¶

In [345]:
special_df["date"] = pd.to_datetime(special_df["date"], format="%d-%m-%Y")

special_df["day_name"] = special_df["date"].dt.day_name()

avg_slots = (
    special_df.groupby(["day_name", "meal_type_id"])["available_slots"]
    .mean()
    .reset_index()
)

day_order = ["Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"]
avg_slots["day_name"] = pd.Categorical(avg_slots["day_name"], categories=day_order, ordered=True)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.barplot(
    data=avg_slots,
    x="day_name",
    y="available_slots",
    hue="meal_type_id",
    palette="Set2"
)

plt.xlabel("Day of Week")
plt.ylabel("Average Available Slots")
plt.title("Average Available Slots per Day of Week by Meal Type")
plt.legend(title="Meal Type ID")
plt.show()

The analysis shows that Sunday has the highest average availability (20.4 slots) while Tuesday records the lowest (9.7 slots). On average, providing around 14 special orders per day would balance the overall demand effectively.¶
